        Chart Review 19/07/24

        Guess who's back, guess who's back, guess who's back, guess who's back, Danana, eh, eh, eh, eh, eh, eh, eh, danana- oh, sorry.

        I'M FINALLY ON TIME!! KIND OF! MY SUMMER HOLIDAYS ARE UP! NOTHING CAN STOP ME NOW!

        Except, maybe, for how utterly static the chart has been in the past couple months. Not to be pedantic or anything, but Dasha's spent so many weeks at 9 and 10 I'm genuinely shocked she hasn't ran for Prime Minister yet. And don't get me started on the Carpenter duology.

        Speaking of which, it's business as usual in the circle of life that is the Sabrina Carpenter 1-2 (Espresso overpowering Please Please Please, if anyone was guessing), as Shaboozey contemplates his life decisions for a 7th (SEVENTH) time in 3rd place. Seriously, how unlucky must he be? I don't care if he ends up a 1-hit wonder, just let him have his moment for one week. It would make my day somewhat easier to enjoy, don't you think?

        Ah well. There's always Eminem. His latest album came out last Friday and if you hadn't already known by now, it's basically one long charade about how his Slim Shady persona is gonna pick up it's P45. And boy, does he not want you to forget it. It also had an actual single, the first time since 2013 he hasn't thrown an LP out and hoped for the best. My thoughts on this are the same for every rap album nowadays. I couldn't care less. But everyone with a Spotify account has naturally taken it to heart, and joining Houdini (up to 4 today) in the UK Top 20 are Habits at 11, where he duets with a guy called White Gold who isn't credited and honestly I couldn't give one if he was, and Renaissance at 13, the traditional Eminem album skit opener where we sit through 90 seconds of your usual white-boy white-hair some-thrills hiphop before suddenly snapping back to reality and realising 'Oh. I'm 51 years old. I shouldn't keep acting like I laugh at Skibidi Toilet jokes and showing off my Drake/Kendrick conspiracy theories.' Besides, he can rhyme orange with banana, so it's kinda hard to disapprove of his antics.

        So Eminem did his thing, obvs, but hot on his heels is the shocking revelation that the England football team has weird musical tastes. Seeing them shaft it in the final on Sunday brought a wry smile on my face, as I could now prepare myself for a safe, unthreatening chart battle. Bang on the money I was. 3 Lions doesn't do as well as it set out to do, only fighting it's way to Number 8, a 4-place drop from the last time 25 million people witnessed the inevitable in 2021. And that disappointment stretches along to the rest of the footie hits. Only 1 other song ends up in the best-sellers, but in a funny twist of events, it's not the one you think. Vindaloo, Sweet Caroline and World In Motion all bottled it after the midweeks, but creeping it's way to 36 is Dancing In The Dark by Bruce Springsteen, a song which got to No.4 nearly forty years ago, but has now found a second wind because people associate it with Phil Foden now. Even though he was GARBAGE at Euro 2024. Hasn't stopped me from loving it. And given Bruce hasn't had a hit since 2002, it's the best we can hope for.

        As usual in weeks like these, the other new hits get sorely overlooked, so thankfully you can always rely on me to give your idols some love. In at 15 is Ice Spice who you could forgive for being somewhat unfortunate in the past 12 months. Ever since she contributed to Boy's A Liar's massive success and popped up on a Taylor Swift song, the new Nicki Minaj has found it tough to get much success. Only her duets with Nicki have ended up Top 40, the likes of Deli and Think U The S*** struggling to make their marks on society as a whole. Maybe a duet with Central Cee can help? It worked for D-Block Europe and Dave, it can work for the lady who real name is an Egyptian goddess (Isis, if anyone had figured that out yet). So yeah, Did It First predictably slams its way into the upper reaches, and could probably do better if it weren't for the literal DESERT that is the Top 10 right now. Just don't admit to anyone that you like it. Because people think CC is a plague spreader. And to be honest, he probably is with the amount of people he can get a hit for.

        As for the other new hit, breaking through the barrier at No.39 is Move, a slightly Afrobeaty tune (better than most dance songs nowadays) by a guy called Adam Port. Normally I'd just end these faceless dance acts here and move on with my life, but I have to alert you to the credits. It's a mess. So you have the Fatboy Slim lookalike that is Adam Port, that's all well and good. Stryv, a guy who helped produce that VULTURES album no one cared about, and, erm..., Spicy Margarita by Jason Derulo and Michael Bublé, he gets one. Adam's label Keinemusik gets one for some arbitrary reason. Orso, a DJ project where Stryv is a member, but not Adam Port, they are apparently good enough for one. And finally, there is under-the-radar singer Malachiii that's been a given a credit. Yeah, no, I am definitely shortening this week whenever this charts. Remember that Baddadan fiasco? I may have contributed to that.

        Outside the 40 and prepare the hype train because Apple by Charli XCX has shot up to No.42, so that's an easy hit next week sorted. Also just outside, I've got a new challenge for you. Try not to make a negative comment about the new Katy Perry song. Because it's dire. The somewhat obvious female empowerment messages, the fact she's working with Dr Luke (remember those allegations? I don't.), the realisation that this song is as dated as spoilt milk. I could go on all day. Not even physical copies could get this higher than 47. It's that bad. Her so-called chart rival Kylie Minogue hasn't fared any better either, My Oh My limping to 63, meanwhile the now independent Kesha swings her way to 88, an album track by Megan Thee Stallion pops up, and Iranian-Dutch powerhouse Sevdalisa finally pops her cherry at 74. Even though, sadly, Alibi reminds me of some generic Latin fluff. Not her fault, of course, but I'm slightly underwhelmed.

        Out today we have albums from Childish Gambino, Jimin, SOFT PLAY, Glass Animals, and Denzel Curry all attempt to get our hopes up, meanwhile NewEra have a new 'song' for us, James Bay drags Noah Kahan along in an attempt to stay relevant, Mabel returns with her new flop (did Look At My Body do anything?), Rex Orange County is back, Paris Paloma shyly slinks back into the spotlight, and the final piece of the Little Mix puzzle has been placed as Jade Thirlwell, sorry, JADE (wouldn't want to confuse her with the girl group now) releases her debut single. After hearing it, it's the best thing from a solo Mixer, but not by that much. So obviously it's gonna go Top 10. Minimum. Ta.
